[agent-review] details:
Narrative:
This change increases the default agent session timeout from 600s (10 min) to 1800s (30 min) and adds a CLI-configurable --timeout flag. The override logic correctly implements Pydantic model defaults with runtime precedence (CLI > YAML > model default). However, the change introduces a critical input validation gap (negative/zero timeouts not caught), lacks documented justification for the 3x increase, and uses generic flag naming inconsistent with other parameters. The impact on wait_for_status() loop logic means invalid timeouts could cause immediate failure (timeout=0) or resource exhaustion (timeout=999999999). Existing YAML tasks with explicit session_timeout values are unaffected; only tasks using defaults change behavior. No test coverage exists to verify the feature works correctly.

Findings:
- [Warning] factory/cli.py:153-177 Add validation to ensure timeout is positive and within reasonable bounds (e.g., 1 ≤ timeout ≤ 7200) before assignment to task.coder.session_timeout
  description: The --timeout parameter accepts any integer value without validation. Users could set --timeout 0 (immediate timeout failure per wait_for_status loop at line 202: 'while elapsed < timeout'), --timeout -100 (loop never executes), or --timeout 999999999 (unbounded resource consumption). The wait_for_status() implementation will immediately return 'timeout' if timeout <= 0, causing task failure without proper error messaging.
- [Warning] factory/models.py:44 Document why the 3x timeout increase from 600s to 1800s was chosen. Add a comment referencing the analysis, GitHub issue, or user feedback that justifies this value.
  description: The session_timeout default was changed from 600 seconds (10 min) to 1800 seconds (30 min) — a 3x increase. This significant value change appears in two places (models.py:44 and cli.py:133) but lacks any comment, commit message explanation, or reference to workload analysis/incident data that would justify this increase. Without documented rationale, it's unclear whether 1800s is the correct value or if this masks agent performance regressions by making timeouts too generous. The review context specifically flags this as a concern area.
- [Info] factory/cli.py:153 Rename --timeout to --session-timeout for consistency and clarity
  description: The flag is named --timeout which is ambiguous in a system with multiple timeout types: session_timeout (coder), eval timeout, crucible timeout, gemini timeout, etc. Other parameters use specific names (--crucible-rounds, --crucible-model, --agent, --model, --effort). Using --timeout without qualification creates confusion about which timeout is being set. More specific naming like --session-timeout or --coder-timeout would match the naming pattern and reduce ambiguity.
- [Warning] <unknown> Add test suite for timeout configuration once testing infrastructure is established. Tests should verify defaults, CLI override precedence, input validation, edge cases, and backward compatibility.
  description: Per CLAUDE.md: 'No tests exist yet — the main way to verify changes is running a task end-to-end.' This critical timing feature should have test coverage for: (1) Default 1800s value is applied when no --timeout specified, (2) CLI override works for both YAML-loaded and inline tasks, (3) Invalid inputs (negative, zero, non-integer) are rejected, (4) Boundary values (1, 7200, max_int) handled correctly, (5) Override only applies when task.coder is non-null. End-to-end testing is insufficient for deterministic timing logic.

